DIV1.P: A NEW BOOKE OF MAPPS, BEING A ready Guide or Direction for any Stran∣ger, or other, who is to Travel in any part of the Cōmon-wealth of England, Scotland, & Ireland.
By which he may know his way in any part thereof, though he knew it not before.

WHEREIN ARE,
I. Alphabeticall Tables, shewing the Longitude and Latitude of all the Towns named in the said Maps; with easie and ready directions how to find any of them, though you know not in what parts they lie.
II. Tables of the High-wayes in ENGLAND, WALES, and IRELAND, Alphabetically methodized; which hath made them very plaine.
III. Tables as easie as an Almanack, which may sup∣ply the use thereof for 100 Yeares, that is to say, from Anno 1600. to 1700.
And other usefull Tables.
By THOMAS PORTER.
This Book being necessary for all men, it is therefore made portable for every mans pocket.

P.HI: Licensed, and entred according to the late Act for Printing.

DIV1.P: To be sold by ROBERT WALTON, at the Rose and Crown at the West end of S. Pauls, 1655.

DIV1.HEAD: To the Reader.
DIV1.P:
I Doubt not but it will seeme strange to all that know me, that I should employ the Press upon such a Subject as this, where∣in the most familiar of my acquaintance could never discover in mee any such in∣tention. The truth is, I am no way ambitious of the Title of an Almanackmaker, much lesse of an Astrologer; the meanesse of the former, and ig∣nominie of the latter, being sufficient to keepe back my desires from running after either. Neverthe∣lesse heere is presented to thy view, that which will tell thee the day of the Month, the fixed Feasts▪ the movable Feasts, the beginning and ending of the Termes▪ the houre of Sunset, and indifferently well the age of the Moone for an Hundred yeares, the greater part whereof is al∣ready expired▪ This I did, because I my selfe have oftener desired to know the time already past, then that which is to come, and per∣haps some others may bee of my minde in this par∣ticular; and for such as care not for that, here is neare Fifty years to come, which I take to bee a competent time for a thing of this nature: As for the principall Matter of this Booke, although
the World abound with plenty of the like, yet have I never seene any, which to my meane ca∣pacity directs so ready a way for the finding out a∣ny Town mentioned therein: and it is not requi∣site that you should foreknow what County or part of the Nation the Towne is in, which you desire to find, if you do but know the name thereof; The Maps are small yet will they do as much as rea∣sonably can bee expected in so little roome: And if this finde a gratefull acceptance, it will encou∣rage me to publish something else of the like kind. In the meane time I subscribe my self

DIV1.HEAD: An Advertisement for the honest Countreyman, who proba∣bly may stand in need hereof, for the understanding of the Book.
DIV1.P: WHereas in some places you read maps in the plural number, and in other places map in the singular number, the word Map is used when both are joyned to∣gether as one (as it is best) but when 'tis bound up in a book, it is too big to be folded up in one; and therefore each part is folded up by it self, which makes two maps (the one containing England, Wales, Ireland, and pa r of Scot∣land; and the other all the rest of Scotland, together with the form and manner of London, Westminster, Oxford, and Edinburgh) and in this sense they are called maps.

By the word (Long Square) you are to understand such a thing as is in the Margent, marked with A. in the illustration
A midst of it: for the small black lines, crossing the map both ways, makes it full of such like long squares, so that there is no Town named in the map, but it must happen to be in some one of those long squares: and every one of them contains a whole de∣gree, as well in longitude as in latitude: and the begin∣ning of the book shws you what degree of longitude and latitude any town is in: so that if you do but know the name onely of the Town (though you do not know in what County it is) this book by shewing you the longitude and latitude, shews you the long square where you may find it in the map: so that you need look no further for
it then that long square, or degree, and having found the town in the map, it also shews you the County it is in.

If you be to travel to any place, for which you have no direction in this book, first find the Town in the map that you are to go from, and also the Town you are to go to; then lay a thread streight upon the map, from the one Town to the other, this thread doth shew you the Towns in the nearest way, if you could travel as streight as you can look. But because the ways are generally crook∣ed therefore you are many times enforced to go out of the streightest way, but be sure you go not far from it, for the nearer you go to that streight line, the less you go about.

If you be to travel to any Town not named in the map, then you must learn between what two Towns named in the map the place you desire to go to stands: and (accord∣ing to the distance from either of them) suppose it were placed in this map; then find your way as aforesaid, by laying your thread to that supposed place; and thus you may do if you be to travel to a place not named in the map. Thus much for the map and the use thereof

DIV1.HEAD: Of the Table of the Highways.
DIV1.P: Forasmuch as many Countrey people do not un∣derstand what a Collumn is, which they must do before they understand the directions for the high∣ways: I shall therefore explain the meaning there∣of by an example or two; that is to say:

Look in the 41 page, you will find the second Town thus: 1. Dulverton 16. 131. now in this example the place where 1. stands, is called the first Collumn, the place where Dul∣verton stands is the second Collumn, the place where 16. stands is called the third Collumn, and the place where 131 stands is called the fourth Collumn.

In the same page look till you find 1 Chipnam, 10. 77. in this example 1. is in the first Collumn, Chipnam in the second, 10. in the third, and 77. in the fourth Collumn: and so of the rest. And now a word or two for the Alma∣nack.

In the use of an ordinary Almanack, these things must be known; that is to say, the year of our Lord, the moneth of the year, and the week of the moneth, else a moneth or week may be mistaken. Now these being known, these tables are as easie as any Almanack, after you know the Sunday Letter for the year desired: which you may easily do by the table in folio 59, and 60. Example;

Suppose the year 1655. in the first Collumn you have the year 1655. in the second Collumn you have 3 which is the Golden Number that year, in the third Collumn you have g. which is the Sunday Letter that year, in the fourth Collumn you have 3. which is the Epact, in the fifth collumn you have 25. which is the number of direction for that year, by which number of direction, and by the Table of the moveable feasts, the said feasts may be known for that or any other year, till 1701.

DIV1.HEAD: Errata.
DIV1.P: NOtwithstanding much care was used to correct the errours, yet some have escaped: it is therefore de∣sired, that the Reader (before he read the book) will first amend with his pen, the three errors noted at the latter end of it: as also in the first page, for explaining of the maps, in the last line but three, for ten minutes, read six minutes, and in the last line, for six minutes, read ten mi∣nutes, pag. 12. for Milford haven 18. 51. read Milford-haven 14. 51. page 41. for Bath 87. read Bath 97. for next to Bath, you must say Maxfield 10. and then the rest in order as they stand, page 44. for Maidenhead t. 6. read Maiden∣head c. 6 page 45. line 2. for former table, read former part, page 45. for Bakway p. 8. read Barkway, p. 7. page 46. for irencester, f. 10. read Cirencester t. 10. page 46. for Dorcester f 13. read Dorcester r. 13. page 46. for Gravesend g. 4. read Gravesend i. 4. page 46. for Hay f. 6 read Hay t. 6. page 46. for Kingstone o. see for Dorchester to London Kingstone 1. page 47. for Litchfield 5. 10. read Litchfield f. 10. page 47. for Newark h. 14. read Newark b. 14. page 47. for Newton C. 3. read Newton t. 3. page 47. for Puckeridge p. 9. read Puckeridge p. 8. page 47 for Royston b. 8. read Royston b. 19 page 48. for Wickham m. 6. read Wickham n. 6. page 53 line 2. for former table read former part, page 54. for Emely h. 6. read Emely i. 6. page 54. for Kilcock, a. 7. read Kilcock a. 6. page 54. for Klmallock h. 5. read Klmallock i. 5. page 55. for Toom Evagh r 5. read Toom Evagh r. 3. page 55. for Tipperary h 7. read Tipperary i. 7.

DIV1.HEAD: A KEY For the Opening or Explaining of the MAPS.
DIV1.P: BEfore we come to the use of the Tables, the Reader is desired to take notice that the top, the bottome, and the sides of this Map are divided into certain black & white parts; ten of which parts on the top, or on the bottome make a degree in lon∣gitude, and six of the parts on either side make a degree in latitude; which degrees are figu∣red as well on the top as on the bottome, to shew the longitude, and they are figured on ei∣ther side, to shew the latitude.

And you may please to note, that every of the black and white parts, or divisions on the top and on the bottom, containe ten minutes; and each of the white and black parts, or divi∣sions on the sides, containe six minutes, and
sixty minutes make a Degree. From the begin∣ning of every degree on the bottome, to the beginning of the same degree on the top, are lines drawne through the Map; these lines are called the lines of longitude. From every de∣gree on the left side to the same degree on the right side, there are also Lines drawn through the Map, which are called the lines of Late, as was said before. This being known, the use followeth.

DIV2.HEAD: How to finde out readily any Towne named in the Table, with the Longitude and Latitude thereof.
DIV2.P: LOoke in the Table following, proper to that Nation or Countrey which the Towne is in, and right against it you have the Longi∣tude of the place in the first Collumne, and in the second Collumne you have the Latitude of the same place.

Example. Suppose that you would finde the longitude and latitude of Bedford. Look in the Alphabeticall table for Bedford among the Towns in England, beginning with B. and right against it you have 20 in the first Column, which shewes that Bedford is in the 20 degree of Longitude: and in the second Collumn you will finde 52. which shewes that Bedford is in the 52. degree of Latitude.

Example. Suppose that you would finde Dublin in Ireland, then you must look into the Alphabeticall Table of or for Ireland, amongst the Townes beginning with the Letter D. and right against Dublin in the first Collumne you will finde 13. which shewes that Dublin is in the 13. degree of longitude; and in the second Collumn you have 53 which shews that Dub∣lin is in the 53. degree of latitude; and so of the rest.

DIV2.HEAD: How to finde out readily in the Map, any Towne named in the same.
DIV2.P: HAving found out by the Rules aforego∣ing, the longitude & latitude of the place, observe where the line of Longitude cuts the line of Latitude, and in the long square above the line of Latitude towards the right hand, you may finde the Towne desired.

Example. Suppose Cambridge be desired to be found, in the Map, I finde that the line of its Longitude is 20. and cuts the line of its Latitude which is 52. in the which square neare the line of Longitude 21. you may finde Cambridge.

Suppose you woud finde Chichester in the Map, you will finde that the line of its Longi∣tude is 19. and cuts the line of its Latitude, which is 50. in a place of the Sea below the
Isle of Wight, marked with a little at above which, before you come at the 51. line of la∣titude, and towards the right hand, before you come at the 20 line of Longitude, you will find Chichester, the place desired.
Note that when a Towne happens to be in a line, it must bee accounted for that degree which is figured at that line, and thus you may easily and readily finde out any place named in the Map.
Note that where you finde two or more Townes of one name, you have the first Letters of the County that each Town is in.

DIV1.HEAD: A Table of the Principall Roades in England and Wales, divided into three Parts.

DIV3.HEAD: In the first Part, take notice, that there is belonging to each Road four Collumes.
DIV3.P: 1 IN the first Collume against so many of the Towns written in a greater Letter as are needfull, is set one of the 24 Letters in or∣der as they be in the Alphabet, and in the same Collume against each Town written in a smal∣ler Letter, there is some one number, as 1. 2. 3. &c. which by the directions of the second Part, readily shewes you how to finde any Towne written in the smaller Letter in this Part.

2 In the second Collume is set down the names of the chiefe Towns in each Road in or∣der as the said Towns lie from London, begin∣ning with the furthest Towne in any Roade from London, which furthest Towns are writ∣ten in a bigger Letter, and are set Alphabe∣tically for the more ready finding out of any of them.

DIV4.HEAD: Example.
DIV4.P: Suppose you would know the way from Dover to London, look for Dover in this second Collume, amongst the Towns written in a bigger Letter (which as is said before, are set Alphabetically) and under it in the same Collume, is set Canterbury, Sittinborn, Rochester, Graves end, and Dartford, which shews that you must passe through those Townes as you go to London, and so of the rest. Note that sometimes a Road breaks off many miles before you come at London, in which case you ever have a Letter and a Number which directs you the rest of the way, as you will understand by the Se∣cond Part.

3 In the third Collume, against every Town, in every Road, is set a number which shews the distance of miles betwixt it and the Town before it. Example: In the said Road from Dover to London, against Canterbury, in this third Collume, is 12. which shewes that the distance betweene Dover and Canterbury is 12. miles.

4 In the fourth Collume right against each Town is set the distance thereof from London. Example, against Dover in this fourth Col∣lume is set 55. and against Canterbury is set 43. which shewes that Dover is 55. miles.
and Canterbury is 43. miles from London.

DIV3.HEAD: The Use of the Second Part.
DIV3.P: IN this Part is set downe Alphabetically all the Townes mentioned in the former Part not therein set down Alphabetically, but Prin∣ted in a smaller Letter, and to each Town in this Part, there is set a Letter and a Number, which Letter and Number if you finde in the first Collume of the First Part. you may therin also find the Town desired. One Example wil make all cleare.

Suppose you desire to know the way from Exeter to London: First looke for Exeter in the First Part amongst the Towns Printed in a bigger Letter, and because yon finde it not a∣mongst them (which if you cou'd do you need not to look in this Part) therefore looke in this Part for Exeter, and you find Exeter in 2 now look for the same Letter and Number, viz. for M. in the first Collume of the first part, and un∣der that M. in the same Collume, looke for 2. against which 2. in the second Collume of the first part you finde Exeter, and the Towns in the way from thence to London, viz. Honing∣ton, Chard, &c.

DIV4.HEAD: Example.
DIV4.P: Suppose you would know the way from Lincoln to London: Look in this part for Lin∣coln, and you will find Lincoln l. 3. which di∣rects you to look for L. in the first Collume of the first part, and for 3. under it in the same Collume, and against that 3. you shall find in the second Collume Lincoln, and under it Sle∣ford Bourne d. 2. which d. 2. directs you to look for the rest of the Towns that you are to passe through, that is, Look for d. in the first Collume of the first part, and under it look for 2. and against 2. you find Bourne, and under Bourne you have West Deeping, Gunworth-ferry, Stilton b 17. which b 17. directs you to looke for B in the first Collume of the First Part, and under it is 17. and against that 17. in the second Collume, is Stilton, Huntington, and the rest of the Townes to London. This Town is put for an example, becuse if you un∣derstand it, you will more easily understand o∣ther places which have fewer references.
You may note that we go according to vul∣gar or common account, but in the North and West they are often long.
The Third Part containes the Crosse Roads which may easily be understood by what hath been sayd before. These directions will serve for the Tables of Ireland, they being done in the same maner.

Tables wherby you may know the day of the month, the fixed feasts, the moveable feasts, the beginning and ending of Tearms, the Sun rising and setting, and the age of the Moon for 100. yeers.
DIV2.P: Suppose you would know the Sunday Letter for the year 1655. Looke under the Title of the yeare of our Lord till you find 1655. and right against it under the title of the Sunday letter, you have g, whch shews that g is the Sunday letter for that year: and in the last Col∣lume under the title of the number of Directions, a∣gainst 1655. you have 25. which shews tha 25. is the number of direction for that year.

DIV2.HEAD: A Table shewing the houre and minute of the Sun-rising for ever.
DIV2.P: te, that so many houres as the sun riseth before Noon, so many hours ette hlter Noon: s if it rise at 4. then it sets at 8. if it rise at 5. the it at 7▪ if it rise at 6. it sets at 6. if it rise at 7. it sets at 5.

DIV2.HEAD: A Table of the moveable Feasts for 100. years.
DIV2.P: Having by the former Table found the number of Direction for the year desired, finde the same number in the first Collume, under the title Direction, and right against it in the Col∣lume under the proper Titles, you have the moveable Feasts for that year. Suppose I would know what day Shrove Sunday is on the year 1655. By the former Table I find the number of Direction to be 25. therfore I look for 25. in the first Collume of this Table, and right against it under the title of Shrove Sunday, I find 25. which shewes that 25. of Feb. is Shrove Sunday
Note, that every fourth year hath two Sunday Letters, because Leap year, the first of which is in use untill the 24 Feb. and the other all the year after.

DIV2.P: The Directions. Having by the former Table found the Sunday Letter, wheresoever you find that Let∣ter in any part of this Table, it shewes that day to be Sunday: and right against it towards the left hand is the day of the Month English Ac∣count: and on the right hand of it is the day of the Month forraign Account.

Example, Suppose you would know what day of the week the 19. of Jan. 1651. By the former Ta∣ble I find the Sunday Letter was e: now be∣cause the Letter e in this Table stands against the 19. day, I conclude that the 19. day was Sunday.

Example. Suppose I would know what day of the week the first day of March 1653. was: By the former Table I finde the Sunday letter to be b, now I look in the month of March against the first day, and I find d: now if b be Sunday, then c is Munday, and d is Tuesday, which shewes that the first of March is Tuesday, and so of any other day or year. Note that on the right hand of any Letter in this Table is set the day of the month Forraign Account.

Example. On the right hand of the letter g, against the 15 day of July is 25. which day is the 25. day of July according to Forraign Account. Note that there is 10. dayes difference between our Account and the Forraign Account, as you wll see if you observe your former directions.

DIV2.HEAD: A Table of the fixed Feasts, and other Dayes of Note, for ever.
DIV2.P: Note, that if that day whereon the Tearme should begin be Sunday, then it begins a day sooner: or if Sunday when it ends, then it con∣tinues a day longer.

DIV2.HEAD: How to find out the age of the Moon.
DIV2.P: TO do this it's necessary to know 2 numbers.

1. The number of every monh of the year, as March is the first month the number thereof is 1. Aprill is the second month, the number whereof is 2. &c. January is the eleventh month, the number thereof is 11. February is the twelfth month, the number thereof is 12.

2. The Epact for the year desired, which may bee known by the former Table for any yeare mentioned therein. Note that the Epact doth not begin til March, so that the Epact for Jan. and Feb. must bee the same with the yeare a∣foregoing.
These two numbers being knowne, adde them together, and substract the sum from 30. the remainder is the day of the Change that month.

DIV3.HEAD: Example.
DIV3.P: Suppose I would know what time the Moon changed in July 1654. the number of the month is 4. the Epact this yeare is 22. adde 22 and 4 it makes 26. take 26. from 30. there re∣mains 4. which shews that the Moon changed the 4 day of July.
If the two numbers make above 30. look how much it is above 30. and take so much from 30. and then the remainder is the day of the change.
If the month have but 30 dayes in it, you must take the remainder from 29.

DIV2.HEAD: A Table shewing the true value of one pound yearly Rent to continue any num∣ber of years under 31. after the rates of 6. and 8. in the hundred, reckning In∣terest upon Interest.
DIV2.P: Example: Suppose I would know what ten pounds yearly value to continue 21. yeares is worth in ready money, after the rate of 6. in the hundred Interest.
By the Table you see that one pound a year to con∣tinue 21. years, is worth 11. pounds, 15. shillings, and 3. pence. Then 10. pounds a year is worth 10. times as much, which may easily be found thus.

DIV3.HEAD: The Ʋse of the Table.
DIV3.P: Finde the principall summe in the first Collume, and the time on the top, and right against the for∣mer, and under the latter, you have the Interest desi∣red.

DIV2.HEAD: A necessary Table for buying and selling any thing by the hundred.
DIV2.P:
By this Table, knowing the price of one pound of any thing, you may know how much the hundred weight (being 112. pound) comes to: or having bought any thing by the hundred weight, you may know how to retaile it by the pound. If one pound
of any thing cost 4 pence 3 farthings, then a hundred weight of the same commodity will cost 2 l. 4 s. 4 d. Likewise if a hundred weight of any thing cost 4 l. 6 s. 4 d. the price of one pound will cost 9 d. q. DIV2.HEAD: The names of severall Maps and Prints, that are Printed, Coloured, and sold by the said ROBERT WALTON.
DIV2.P: THis Map, with a Description, and a briefe Chro∣nology of all the remarkable passages and actions that have happened ever since the long Parliament be∣gan 1640. to this present yeare; and this is a most commodious Ornament for every mans house, and therefore you may either have it in paper coloured, or not, or else on Cloth, with or without Rollers and Ledges, or you may have it inlarged with severall Pi∣ctures, as the 5 Senses, the 4 Seasons, the 4 Elements, and the Cries of London, and the like.
Or you may have the Map alone.
Or England, Wales, and Ireland by it selfe.
One Sheet-plate of the 5 Senses.
One of the 4 Seasons.
One of the 4 Elements.
One of the 4 parts of the World.
And one of Once a Man and Twice a Childe, or the severall Ages of Men and Women, shewing their rising and falling, both of high and low, rich and poor, from the Cradle to the Grave.

Lastly 1. Almanack in a Royal sheet for fifty years,
with the Pictures of the 4 Seasons, the 7 Planets, the 7 liberall Sciences, the 4 times of the dy the 4 Ele∣ments about it, the which is usefull for Gentlemens, and Schollars Studies, Tradesmens Shops, and the Countreymans house.
Though these onely are named, yet he hath divers others, and purposeth more, as time and opportunity will admit.
He hath choice of Dutch things likewise.

Such is the Usefulness and necessaryness hereof that it is not only for Ornament of the House but for all occasions, and persons; but chiefly for Com∣manders Traveller and such as keep Fayres▪ as also Sea-faring Men because it sheweth the manner of the Sea Coasts about all the aforesayd places
I have therefore Contrived it that it may be portable for every mans pocket.

Reader, If you would know the distance of any place herein, you must first know the Scale of miles, and that the small space of White therein is one mile and the black another, and so you will see what the Whole or any part thereof is, Then take a Payr of Compasses and Measure from the one place to the other that you would know the distance of As suppose you would know how farr it is from London to North-Hampton you must set one point of your Compass in the round spot of London, and the other into the like spot in North-Hāpton, and then Carry your Compass to the Scale of Miles and you will see that it is :52: Miles, but if it should bee more Miles then the Scale is long then you may take :50: and Widen or lessen your compass as you see cause and then try by the Scale, but withall carry your eye and hand and directly from place to place in takeing distances as you can, so you haue the Just distance of any place.
